{{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy|21st-century philosophy]] |color = |image = |name = '''Christian Barry''' |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = [[Analytic philosophy|Analytic]] | institutions = [[Australian National University]] |main_interests = [[political philosophy]], [[moral philosophy]] | thesis_title = The Contribution Principle: Its Meaning and Significance for Allocating Responsibility to Address Acute Deprivation | thesis_url = | thesis_year = 2005 | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = |notable_ideas = | spouse = | education = | alma_mater = [[Columbia University]] |influences = |awards = Outstanding Researcher Award ([[Australian Research Council|ARC]]), Global Ethics Fellow ([[Carnegie Council]]), Leverhulme Visiting Fellowship |website = http://christianbarry.net }}
'''Christian Barry''' is an American philosopher and Professor of [[Philosophy]] at the [[Australian National University]]. He is a co-editor of the ''[[Journal of Political Philosophy]]'' and a former head of the School of Philosophy in the Research School of the Social Sciences at the ANU. Barry is known for his research on [[Global justice|international justice]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pavlakos |first1=George |title=Review of Responding to Global Poverty: Harm, Responsibility, and Agency |journal=[[Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews]] |date=22 May 2017 |url=https://ndpr.nd.edu/news/responding-to-global-poverty-harm-responsibility-and-agency/ |accessdate=13 August 2018 |issn=1538-1617}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Philosophy on the Small Screen |url=https://blog.apaonline.org/2017/09/21/philosophy-on-television/ |website=Blog of the APA |accessdate=13 August 2018 |date=21 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=A Conversation with Christian Barry, Editor of the Journal of Political Philosophy |url=http://wileyactual.com/wileyhumanitiesfest/2017/09/06/a-conversation-with-christian-barry-editor-of-the-journal-of-political-philosophy/ |website=[[Wiley Humanities Festival]] |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Christian Barry |url=https://www.carnegiecouncil.org/people/christian-barry |website=[[Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs]] |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Poverty Alleviation, Global Justice, and the Real World - Ethics & International Affairs |journal=[[Ethics & International Affairs]] |date=8 September 2017 |url=https://www.ethicsandinternationalaffairs.org/2017/poverty-alleviation-global-justice-and-the-real-world/ |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fiona |first1=Woollard, |title=Barry and Øverland on Doing, Allowing, and Enabling Harm |journal=[[Ethics & Global Politics]] |date=25 September 2017 |url=https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/414440/ |accessdate=13 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Christian was a program officer at the [[Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs]] before joining the ANU<ref>{{cite web |title=Christian Barry |url=https://www.policyforum.net/authors/christian-barry/ |website=[[Policy Forum]] |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref> and is the [[Ethics Matters]] podcast co-presenter.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://ethicsmatterstvseries.com/about-us/ |website=[[Ethics Matters]] |accessdate=13 August 2018 |language=en-AU}}</ref>
