The '''Honor Concept'''<ref name="History of Honor at Naval Academy">{{cite web|last=Shaw |first=Steven |title=Naval Academy Honor Concept Strays From Roots |url=http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/guest-column-naval-academy-honor-concept-strays-from-roots/article_f3b4151b-da04-5df1-a047-f3e1ef525d85.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140201064011/http://www.capitalgazette.com/news/guest-column-naval-academy-honor-concept-strays-from-roots/article_f3b4151b-da04-5df1-a047-f3e1ef525d85.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=1 February 2014 |accessdate=1 February 2014 }}</ref> and '''Honor Treatise''' are parts of the [[United States Naval Academy|United States Naval Academy's]] Honor Program. Similar to the [[Cadet Honor Code]]s of the [[United States Military Academy]] and [[United States Air Force Academy]], the Concept formalizes the requirement for midshipmen to demonstrate integrity while refusing to lie, cheat or steal.<ref name=USNAConcept>''Honor Concept'', USNA Brigade Honor Program website</ref>

The Treatise adopts the use of first-person point of view, becoming a personal call to obey the letter and spirit of the Concept amongst midshipmen of the brigade.<ref name=USNATreatise>''Honor Treatise'', USNA Brigade Honor Program website</ref> The [[United States Coast Guard Academy]] utilizes a similar Honor Concept to impart the same call to integrity for its corps of cadets.<ref name=USCGAConcept>''Honor Concept'', USCGA website, Cadet Life section</ref>

Unlike the other service academies' honor codes, the Honor Concept allows a midshipman to confront someone committing an honor violation without formally reporting it.  At the other academies, failure to formally report an honor violation is construed as tolerating it, which is itself a violation of the code.

Penalties for violating the Honor Concept can be severe, up to and including expulsion from the Academy.

{{quote|Midshipmen are persons of integrity: We stand for that which is right.

We tell the truth and ensure that the full truth is known. We do not lie.

We embrace fairness in all actions. We ensure that work submitted as our own is our own, and that assistance received from any source is authorized and properly documented. We do not cheat.

We respect the property of others and ensure that others are able to benefit from the use of their own property. We do not steal.|Honor Concept|USNA Brigade Honor Program<ref name=USNAConcept/>}}

==History==
The principles of the Honor Concept are as old as the Academy itself, revolving around the principle that an officer's word is his bond.  However, examination of the past academy honor practices by 1953 USNA class president [[Ross Perot]] discovered "no uniform policy for dealing with midshipmen who had violated their class's conception of honor."<ref name=Gelfand191>Gelfand, ''Sea change at Annapolis'', p. 191</ref> While admitting to ''irreverence'' as an "inescapable trait of midshipmen," brigade leaders like Perot, [[William P. Lawrence]] and [[James Sagerholm]] worked with Brigade Captain [[Charles Dobony]] and academy superintendent [[Harry W. Hill]] to create the Honor Concept.<ref name=Gelfand192>Gelfand, p. 192</ref>

