[[File:Zimara - Questio de primo cognito - 4776273 F.tif|thumb|''Questio de primo cognito'']] '''Marcantonio Zimara''' (c. 1460–1532 CE), was an Italian philosopher.
==Life== He was born in [[San Pietro in Galatina|Galatina]] (Lecce) and from 1497 studied philosophy at the [[University of Padua]] under [[Agostino Nifo]] and [[Pietro Pomponazzi]]. He subsequently taught logic while studying medicine at Padua (1501–1505), and in 1509 was appointed professor of natural philosophy. From 1509 to 1518 Zimara lived in San Pietro in Galatina, after which he taught in [[University of Salerno|Salerno]] (1518–1522), [[University of Naples Federico II|Naples]] (1522–1523), and again at Padua (1525–1528).
Zimara edited works by medieval philosophers (notably [[Albertus Magnus]]) and edited and wrote commentaries on [[Aristotle]] and [[Averroës]]. His ''Tabula dilucidationum in dictis Aristotelis et Averrois'' (1537), became the principal scholarly tool for searching the works of Aristotle and Averroës.
