{{Augustine}}
The '''''Soliloquies of Augustine''''' is a two-book document written by the 4th-century saint [[Augustine of Hippo]].<ref>''Soliloquies: Augustine's Inner Dialogue'' by Boniface Ramsey 2000 {{ISBN|978-1-56548-142-8}} page 1</ref>

The book has the form of an "inner dialogue" in which questions are posed, discussions take place and answers are provided, leading to self-knowledge.<ref>''Augustine's Inner Dialogue: The Philosophical Soliloquy in Late Antiquity'' by Brian Stock 2010 {{ISBN|978-0-521-19031-2}} page 6</ref> The first book begins with an inner dialogue which seeks to know a soul. In the second book it becomes clear that the soul Augustine wants to get to know is his own.<ref>''The Cambridge companion to Augustine'' by Eleonore Stump, Norman Kretzmann 2001 {{ISBN|0-521-65985-X}} page 76</ref>

